# B Bayesian modeling based on the partial likelihood for multivariate distributions 

Next we demonstrate how to incorporate adaptive partitioning in multivariate spaces using the partial likelihood following the OPT prior, which essentially imposes a Bayesian CART prior on the tree splitting. Specifically, for each potential tree node $A$, we adopt a multinomial prior on $J(A)$ over the available dimensions to divide. That is, $J(A) \in\{1,2, \ldots, d\}$ is a multinomial Bernoulli variable with probability $\boldsymbol{\lambda}(A)=\left(\lambda_{1}(A), \lambda_{2}(A), \ldots, \lambda_{d}(A)\right)$ where $0 \leq \lambda_{j}(A) \leq 1$ for all $j$ and $\sum_{j} \lambda_{j}(A)=1$. Given that $J(A)=j$, then we divide $A$ in the $j$ th dimension into the two children $A_{j, l}$ and $A_{j, r}$ and the splitting variable $J\left(A_{j, l}\right)$ and $J\left(A_{j, r}\right)$ are further generated in the same way. The partial likelihood of $(f, \boldsymbol{J})$ then follows the expression in Eq. (2.4).

We can again express the partial likelihood in a scale-free fashion in terms of the likelihoodratio with respect to a base measure $H$. Let

$$
r_{j}(A)=\frac{m_{\mathrm{P}, j}(A)}{H\left(A_{j, l}|A\rangle^{n\left(A_{j, l}\right)} H\left(A_{j, r} \mid A\right)^{n\left(A_{j, r}\right)}}
$$

Then for $J(A)=j$,

$$
\frac{L_{\mathrm{P}}(f, \boldsymbol{J} ; \boldsymbol{x}, A)}{L_{\mathrm{P}}(h, \boldsymbol{J} ; \boldsymbol{x}, A)}=r_{j}(A) \frac{L_{\mathrm{P}}\left(f, \boldsymbol{J} ; \boldsymbol{x}, A_{j, l}\right)}{L_{\mathrm{P}}\left(h, \boldsymbol{J} ; \boldsymbol{x}, A_{j, l}\right)} \frac{L_{\mathrm{P}}\left(f, \boldsymbol{J} ; \boldsymbol{x}, A_{j, r}\right)}{L_{\mathrm{P}}\left(h, \boldsymbol{J} ; \boldsymbol{x}, A_{j, r}\right)}
$$

where for each $j L_{\mathrm{P}}(h ; \boldsymbol{x}, A)=H\left(A_{j, l}|A\rangle^{n\left(A_{j, l}\right)} H\left(A_{j, r} \mid A\right)^{n\left(A_{j, r}\right)} \cdot L_{\mathrm{P}}\left(h ; \boldsymbol{x}, A_{j, l}\right) \cdot L_{\mathrm{P}}\left(h ; \boldsymbol{x}, A_{j, r}\right)$.
Moreover, one can compute the exact posterior distribution of $\boldsymbol{J}$ by integrating out the conditional prior on $f$, such as the PT, as follows. Let $\Phi(A)=\int L_{\mathrm{P}}(f ; \boldsymbol{x}, \boldsymbol{J}, A) \pi(d f, d \boldsymbol{J})$. Then $\Phi(A)$ can be computed recursively

$$
\Phi(A)=\iint L_{\mathrm{P}}(f ; \boldsymbol{x}, \boldsymbol{J}, A) \pi(d f \mid \boldsymbol{J}) \pi(d \boldsymbol{J})=\sum_{j} \lambda_{j}(A) M_{j}(A) \Phi\left(A_{j, l}\right) \Phi\left(A_{j, r}\right)
$$

where $M_{j}(A)=\int m_{j}(A) \pi\left(\mathrm{d} F\left(A_{j, l} \mid A\right)\right)$. Again, the integral term in the middle is simply a beta function when beta priors are adopted on $F\left(A_{j, l} \mid A\right)$. Correspondingly, the posterior probability for $J(A)=j$ given the training data $\boldsymbol{x}$ is $\mathrm{P}(J(A)=j \mid \boldsymbol{x})=\lambda_{j}(A) M_{j}(A)$. $\Phi\left(A_{j, l}\right) \Phi\left(A_{j, r}\right) / \Phi(A)$.

The conditional posterior for $f$ given $\boldsymbol{J}$ is exactly the same as in the case with a predetermined partition tree. One can similarly write the above recursion in a normalized fashion in terms of the likelihood ratio with respect to the base density $\phi(A)=\Phi(A) / \prod_{x \in A} h(x \mid A)$. In which case $\phi(A)=\sum_{j} \lambda_{j}(A) \eta_{j}(A) \phi\left(A_{j, l}\right) \phi\left(A_{j, r}\right)$ where $\eta_{j}(A)=\int r_{j}(A) \pi(d f, d \boldsymbol{J})=M_{j}(A) / H\left(A_{j, l}|A\rangle^{n\left(A_{j, l}\right)} H\left(A_{j, r} \mid A\right)^{n\left(A_{j, r}\right)}\right.$. Accordingly, $\mathrm{P}(J(A)=j \mid \boldsymbol{x})=\lambda_{j}(A) \eta_{j}(A) \cdot \phi\left(A_{j, l}\right) \Phi\left(A_{j, r}\right) / \phi(A)$.

Furthermore, one can specify the conditional model on $f$ given the tree using latent state variables. When the underlying latent states are modeled using a Markov process,

for example, one can still follow the recipe described previously and arrive at the following expression for the marginal likelihood on $A$, after integrating out both the state variables as well as the splitting variables

$$
\Phi_{s}(A)=\sum_{j} \sum_{s^{\prime} \in \mathcal{S}} \lambda_{j}(A) \rho_{s, s^{\prime}}(A) M_{j, s^{\prime}}(A) \Phi_{s^{\prime}}\left(A_{j, l}\right) \Phi_{s^{\prime}}\left(A_{j, r}\right)
$$

where for all $s, M_{j, s}(A)=\int m_{\mathrm{P}, j}(A) \cdot \pi_{s}\left(\mathrm{~d} F\left(A_{l} \mid A\right)\right)$. Intuitively, $\Phi_{s}(A)$ is the marginal likelihood for $A$ given that $S\left(A_{p}\right)=s$.

Even though we had specified the priors for $\boldsymbol{S}$ and $\boldsymbol{J}$ independently, a posteriori they are dependent. So we must describe the joint posterior of $(\boldsymbol{J}, \boldsymbol{S})$, which is jointly a Markov process. Specifically, the posterior transition probability for $(J(A), S(A))$ is
$\mathrm{P}\left(J(A)=j^{\prime}, S(A)=s^{\prime} \mid J\left(A_{p}\right)=j, S\left(A_{p}\right)=s, \boldsymbol{x}\right)=\lambda_{j^{\prime}}(A) \rho_{s, s^{\prime}}(A) M_{j^{\prime}, s^{\prime}} \Phi_{s^{\prime}}\left(A_{j^{\prime}, l}\right) \Phi_{s^{\prime}}\left(A_{j^{\prime}, r}\right) / \Phi_{s}(A)$.
Note that the dependence on $J\left(A_{p}\right)=j$ is implicit as it determines the node $A$. Given the values of $(\boldsymbol{J}, \boldsymbol{S})$, the conditional posterior of $F$ boils down to the standard univariate PT.

All of the above expressions can be written in terms of the likelihood ratio with respect to the base density by replacing $\Phi_{s}(A)$ with $\phi_{s}(A)=\Phi_{s}(A) / \prod_{x \in A} h(x \mid A)$ and $M_{j, s}(A)$ with $\eta_{j, s}(A)=M_{j, s}(A) /\left(H\left(A_{j, l} \mid A\right)^{n\left(A_{j, l}\right)} H\left(A_{j, r} \mid A\right)^{n\left(A_{j, r}\right)}\right)$. That is

$$
\phi_{s}(A)=\sum_{j} \sum_{s^{\prime} \in \mathcal{S}} \lambda_{j}(A) \rho_{s, s^{\prime}}(A) \eta_{j, s^{\prime}}(A) \phi_{s^{\prime}}\left(A_{j, l}\right) \phi_{s^{\prime}}\left(A_{j, r}\right)
$$

and
$\mathrm{P}\left(J(A)=j^{\prime}, S(A)=s^{\prime} \mid J\left(A_{p}\right)=j, S\left(A_{p}\right)=s, \boldsymbol{x}\right)=\lambda_{j^{\prime}}(A) \rho_{s, s^{\prime}}(A) \eta_{j^{\prime}, s^{\prime}} \phi_{s^{\prime}}\left(A_{j^{\prime}, l}\right) \phi_{s^{\prime}}\left(A_{j^{\prime}, r}\right) / \phi_{s}(A)$.
This gives a complete characterization of the marginal posterior of $(\boldsymbol{J}, \boldsymbol{S})$. Given $(\boldsymbol{J}, \boldsymbol{S})$, the conditional posterior of $F$ is simply that of the corresponding PT model. We provide numerical examples for inference on multivariate sample spaces in Section 4.2.

# C Additional details and results of the numerical experiments 

We report additional numerical results for the univariate and multivariate simulations previously discussed.

## C. 1 Univariate OPT
## C.1.1 OPT PPD Computation

The OPT posterior mean is computed exactly for univariate examples with the recursive algorithm for latent-state models in Section 3.3.

## C.1.2 Results for $L_{1}, L_{\infty}$

Figure S1 reports the $\log L_{1}, L_{\infty}$ risks obtained under the same experiments discussed in Section 4.1. Both metrics generally suggest the same patterns already observed in the $L_{2}$ risk: a steep decrease in the first few tree depths and then plateau around some value, with the partial-likelihood tree having better performance than the full-likelihood tree in the low to medium depth for the $\operatorname{Beta}(500,20)$ and Mixture cases. However, these patterns are not as regular as in $L_{2}$, especially when considering a sample size of 500 and the $L_{\infty}$ metric, which, having a more local nature, is more sensitive to lower sample sizes than the other two metrics.

## C. 2 Bivariate OPT
## C.2.1 Construction of the Generalized Beta Density.

The generalized beta densities used in the bivariate density estimation problems were constructed as follows. Let $G_{0} \sim \operatorname{Gamma}\left(\alpha_{0}, \beta_{0}\right), G_{1} \sim \operatorname{Gamma}\left(\alpha_{1}, \beta_{1}\right)$ and $G_{2} \sim \operatorname{Gamma}\left(\alpha_{2}, \beta_{2}\right)$ be three independent gamma random variables, with $\alpha_{1}, \beta_{i}>0$ for $i=0,1,2$. The joint density of $X=G_{1} /\left(G_{1}+G_{0}\right)$ and $Y=G_{2} /\left(G_{2}+G_{0}\right)$, with $x, y \in(0,1)$ has the form

$$
f(x, y)=\frac{1}{B\left(\alpha_{0}, \alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}\right)} \frac{\lambda_{1}^{\alpha_{1}} x^{\alpha_{1}-1}(1-x)^{-\left(\alpha_{1}+1\right)} \lambda_{2}^{\alpha_{2}} y^{\alpha_{2}-1}(1-y)^{-\left(\alpha_{2}+1\right)}}{\left[1+\lambda_{1} x /(1-x)+\lambda_{2} y /(1-y)\right]^{\alpha_{0}+\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}}}
$$

and $\lambda_{i}=\beta_{i} / \beta_{0}$ for $i=1,2$ and $B\left(\alpha_{0}, \alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}\right)=\prod_{i=0,1,2} \Gamma\left(\alpha_{i}\right) / \Gamma\left(\sum \alpha_{i}\right)$ ).

## C.2.2 OPT PPD Computation

In the bivariate OPT examples, we compute the posterior mean through Monte Carlo samples of the trees. This method is straightforward to implement in a setting where randomizing the splitting dimension for a set requires accounting for all possible children generated by that set. For each MC run, we first compute the message passing recursion terms as in

Section 3.3 for all possible sets generated through all possible trees, to compute posterior stopping probabilities and splitting probabilities along each dimension. Next, we sample a tree using a top-down algorithm: for an available set, we sample a latent state (determining stopping and non-stopping) with the posterior stopping probability and next we sample a splitting dimension using the posterior splitting probability conditional on the sampled state and compute its children. Given such a tree, we evaluate the posterior mean on the tree in a way similar to the univariate case in Section 3.3. We repeat this procedure for 1000 MC runs and average the tree-conditional posterior predictive to estimate the unconditional posterior mean. We use this approach to estimate the posterior mean (i.e., the posterior predictive density) under both the partial-likelihood and full-likelihood specifications.

# C.2.3 Results for $L_{1}, L_{\infty}$ 

Figure S2 reports the $\log L_{1}, L_{\infty}$ risks obtained under the scenarios described in Section 4.2. Again, they suggest similar patterns to those already discussed based on the $L_{2}$ risk, with the partial likelihood tree being the preferable model in the presence of high-density spikes. However, the discrepancy between the two tree specifications is less neat according to these two metrics. For example, the $L_{1}$ distance for the Mixture examples displays better performance of the partial model only for tree depths in the medium-high range. The $L_{1}$ partial model gains are less evident for the Generalized Beta II than in the $L_{2}$ case, and the Generalized Beta III shows comparable (if not better) performance of the full-likelihood tree. On the other hand, $L_{\infty}$ shows major advantages of the partial model in the presence of high spikes and for higher sample sizes $(5000-50000)$. However, it displays a rather "jumpy" behavior, probably due to the extremely local nature of such a metric.

abstract:
Tree-based priors for probability distributions are usually specified using a
predetermined, data-independent collection of candidate recursive partitions of
the sample space. To characterize an unknown target density in detail over the
entire sample space, candidate partitions must have the capacity to expand
deeply into all areas of the sample space with potential non-zero sampling
probability. Such an expansive system of partitions often incurs prohibitive
computational costs and makes inference prone to overfitting, especially in
regions with little probability mass. Thus, existing models typically make a
compromise and rely on relatively shallow trees. This hampers one of the most
desirable features of trees, their ability to characterize local features, and
results in reduced statistical efficiency. Traditional wisdom suggests that
this compromise is inevitable to ensure coherent likelihood-based reasoning in
Bayesian inference, as a data-dependent partition system that allows deeper
expansion only in regions with more observations would induce double dipping of
the data. We propose a simple strategy to restore coherency while allowing the
candidate partitions to be data-dependent, using Cox's partial likelihood. Our
partial likelihood approach is broadly applicable to existing likelihood-based
methods and, in particular, to Bayesian inference on tree-based models. We give
examples in density estimation in which the partial likelihood is endowed with
existing priors on tree-based models and compare with the standard,
full-likelihood approach. The results show substantial gains in estimation
accuracy and computational efficiency from adopting the partial likelihood.
